text: Okay, let's start by sharing your experience of being recruited into the MN program about two or three years back. So, for me, I think probably first I made myself, I made it quite clear to my bosses that I'm interested in clinical, so I was in the clinical interest. So, usually during our appraisal, there's always the three years and five years plan. So, mine was always three years to take the MN course and five years to become an APN. So, it was known right from the start. Okay, so, but specifically, I mean you spoke about clinical track, but did you know that you want to be a nurse clinician or an advanced practice nurse? Oh, I knew I want to be an advanced practice nurse. So, actually back in undergraduate days, we had a lecture by an APN then. Yeah, I think she was a Cardio APN and I was quite inspired by her then. So, I knew this was the track I wanted to take. So, you only expressed your interest through your appraisal? Actually, usually for us, they will speak to us, they will on and off be informal or formal. So, every time they come and talk to me, my answer will be the same. I want to go down the APN track. When you talk about they, who do you refer to? So far, in nursing, there will be your direct court supervisor, usually the court assistant, and we have the assistant director of nursing who actually oversee a few wards. So, I actually made myself quite clear to both the direct supervisor and also assistant director of nursing. When they make their rounds. At that point, how many years are you into your RN role? I think I was probably the first year, I was actually known that I wanted to go down this route. But I mean, because of the SMB requirements as a first year RN, you wouldn't qualify for the MN program. Did your organization sort of prepare you for it? So, they actually sent me for the advanced diploma program, specialization that I was interested in. So, I actually went for advanced diploma one year plus after I started working. And then when I came back, they actually, I continued what I was doing before that. But then just around a few months to a year before I started my program, they sent me out for rotation to different clinical wards with different specialists. Do you happen to know if there were certain things that your superiors were looking out for when recruiting you into this track? Certain things, so what I heard is they would want a person with good academic results. At least because I heard there is a 3-year program. So, another one would be one who demonstrated clinical interest during day-to-day ward rounds. Because someone that is somewhat recognized by the medical counterparts, because you will be working very closely with them. So, I guess they also seek opinion from the doctors in the ward, maybe who they work with on the ground and all. Okay, maybe you can share a bit more also about your current APN career track, right? Which phase are you in? Okay, I'm currently doing my internship. So, I'm reaching the midpoint. So, following that, I'll be taking my national exam at the end of this year. And then if I successfully pass, I'll pass out next year. Okay, so now I'm going to touch a bit about gender. So, when your superior was selecting potential APNs, do you think that they considered the gender of the nurse? I don't think gender actually is a deal-breaker in that sense. Or you must be a female or you cannot be. I don't think so, but it just so happened that in my ward, there are just very few male nurses. And those who were present in my ward, they just didn't express interest in this route. So, I won't say it's because of any gender bias, but they selected me. So, if I would phrase it a bit differently, do you think that it was easier or more difficult for you to be selected into the MN program previously because you were female? I don't think there's a difference actually. So, it's neither more difficult nor easier actually. Why do you say that though? Because I feel what they had in mind then was they had certain attributes that they are looking for in an APN. And gender is definitely not one of them. So, they have things like, okay, next time we want the APN to be a jack-of-all-trades. So, you have to be doing a little bit of research, a little bit of clinicals. They wanted the APN to be someone who is able to at least communicate decently. So, there's certain criteria that they were looking out for and gender is not one of them. Okay. I suppose there's an interview process to being selected. Maybe you can tell me a bit about that. So, the interview process mainly was to reinforce. So, they can just ask us, why do you want to take on this job? Because it's going to be a two-year rigorous program. It's going to be a one-year internship. It's not like a short duration. You have to actually commit to it. So, they wanted to ensure that we are up for this, we are ready for this. And then, they actually asked us what we intend to do next time when you pass out. And of course, what do you think your strengths, your weakness and how to work on that. After being selected, did your superiors speak about things like your life stage, like your personal life stage? Do you have plans of settling down and all that? Yeah. So, they talked about it's advisable not to have a baby in this period of time because it's going to be hard to cope with your studies and internship. Even though it's not like they do not allow you to, but you can tell that it's generally discouraged because of the intensity of the course. They did ask what's your plan in terms of personal life in the next few years. And then, what did you say to your interviewer? I think because I was still young then, so to me that wasn't an issue. But this has been an issue I saw amongst some of my other colleagues that had plans initially. And because they are in different stage of life, it actually is a deterrence for them to go on this program. So, you are speaking about your female colleagues or your male colleagues? Female colleagues actually. Okay. So, now considering this about life stages, childbearing, do you then now think that it will be more difficult for a female to get selected into the program? I don't think it's more difficult for a female to get selected, but rather there will be more consideration for a female to see whether she wants to get on this program or not. Because some common things I heard will be like, if I go on this program, does it mean that I can't give birth in the next three years? Does it mean that you have to take a step back from your family life for the next three years? So, I realized that friends with very young, just given birth with very young kids, they are the ones that struggle the most. Compared to people whose kids are pretty old already, they can actually spend more time on their studies instead of taking care of their child. So, there is a difference, but it's not so much the criteria to be selected, but rather whether one wants to take on that role to go on this study or not. Do you then think that there are gender biases present in the professional development of RNs in the workforce? Not just pertaining to development into an APN track, but across all tracks. Do you think that there is a gender bias? I don't think there is a gender bias, but because even though the percentage of male nurses have increased over the year, it's actually in a slow, gradual increase. So, people who are already in a senior position, the majority are actually female nurses already. Sometimes, what you are looking out for, sometimes when people look out for the next generation of leaders, they will look out for people with similar characteristics. Therefore, I feel that probably, unknowingly sometimes, they may actually feel that females generally possess the same characteristics, knowing the same thing as what they can bring to the workforce. So, probably certain supervisors will be a bit more geared towards that, unknowingly. Are you implying that female leaders tend to look for someone that is similar to them, and it happens to be a female nurse that would exhibit similar traits? Sometimes. But that being said, I feel that even though male nurses are under minority, there is a certain advantage to it. I have seen male nurses, if you are good, you are actually much more easily recognised than your female counterparts, because they are so scarce. If one stood out, that person can be given a lot more opportunities compared to his peers who are females. Because he just stands out more easily, because he is a male, and he can just outshine, because he is a male and he can do his good, compared to his female counterparts, he just managed to get some upper hand. So, are you just to clarify, are you implying that if a male and a female nurse does the same quality of work, same competency, but the male will seem more outstanding? Probably because of certain, sometimes when, be it, I don't know whether there is some masculine characteristics, compared to a male and a female, if they are of equal level of competence, of knowledge, and because of how rare it is to get a male who is very good, because there are so few males around, sometimes that person may be getting a bit more opportunities, at least shine out a bit more. Just because he is so different, right? Correct. Then do you think that nursing leaders take into consideration the gender of the RN when nominating him or her for the MM programme? I don't think so. I don't think that matters at all. I don't think that is part of the consideration. But probably it just so happens because there are more, there are certain criteria for you to get enrolled into the MM programme, one of which is experience. Previously, the majority of the candidates are actually in the nurse clinician stage. So, in the first place, among the nurse clinicians, it is really female-predominated because of previous enrollment characteristics. So, that is the reason why there are more female APNs compared to male. I understand. In your organisation, do you have any male colleagues that are APNs? We used to have one, but he left us. Do you know why he left? I think he was just, he actually, he was quite, he has been an APN for quite some time. And then, he feels that he wasn't, I think at that point in time, there was some ambiguity. So, he feels that he was not practising at all his life. And due to personal reasons, he chose to leave us. So, that was quite in the early stages. Yes. Okay. Just now, so, okay. So, apart from this one other APN, do you know of any other male APN in the APN workforce? Yes. Not in this hospital, but in other hospitals, yes. And would you agree with me that there's very few of them? Definitely. There are much fewer than female. So, you mentioned in your ward that there are also very few males. But these few male nurses, they don't exhibit interest in the APN track. Do you happen to know why? I feel it. I don't think it's due to, okay, I've honestly, I've never wondered why they have no interest in being an APN. Because to me, it's not about, or because you're male or you're female. Yeah. Because whether you have a clinical interest or not. And then, quite a few of my male friends back in undergrad, they actually chose to take on administrative lead research. So, they chose to further their study shortly after entering the profession. So, maybe two or three years into the profession. I'm not too sure, because one of it is, for APN, you need five years to go on this course. I don't know if some males will have the, to them, it's still quite, you know, five years to go on this course, another two years of study, another one year of intern, eight years to become an APN. Probably, to them, they will have gone on to, they have a need to organize, they have a goal to do other things. Be it research, be it policy, et cetera. But why do you think that males have a greater tendency to not want to wait it out? I think it's always the societal pressure for a male having to be the main breadwinner, even though times are changing. But to them, there's, I think in general, there's still this mentality that, okay, if I'm going to get married and support my family, I need to be, I need to earn as much as I can, per se. So, do I, should I wait, like, and even for five years as a minimum, it doesn't mean five years you will definitely go for the course, right? So I may need a minimum of eight years to go it, you know. So sometimes, probably if I go on to take another higher education, I could actually do it much earlier. Based on your experience and observation, male RNs tend to go into research? No, actually, the undergrads are at risk. Those who actually have a degree, they tend to gravitate more towards policy, towards research. Okay, so that's where we are losing our male graduates to. For clinicals. That's interesting, because I would think that there is this stereotype amongst men that they are more clinical. Do you think my stereotype is wrong? I think, I don't think they feel that, okay, at least what I've seen is they feel they are, so if you look, I think if you look across the different specialty, there will always be a few specialty that are more male than other specialty. For example, in the emergency department, in the ICU, in the OTE. So I guess that to them, probably, they will feel that, okay, they can, they will have advantage in this, in such things, be it in terms of physical strength or whatsoever. But not so much because I think they are better in clinical, per se. So you would think, okay, so maybe let's explore a bit deeper. Why would you think that, why do you think that there are more male prominent in the ED and ICU and OT? I feel, okay, I can't speak too much about OT, but at least for ED and ICU, one thing is it's a faster pace and then it's more action-packed. In terms of, as I said, ED, in terms of physical strength, in terms of violent patient and all, and this could be the attribute that actually draw male nurses into that specialty. So compared to general ward, per se, when one has to take on many patients, you have to attend to the basic care, I don't think, probably this part will not seem as attractive to them, compared to the fast-paced, faster-paced ED and ICU environment. That's a very interesting observation. Then do you think, because now, I mean, we both agree that there are so few men in the APM practice, do you think that there is, because, maybe let me share some statistics with you. So currently we have 11% of males in the RN workforce, which is already a great improvement from the past. But now, currently in our APM workforce, we only have about 5%. So there's a, it's not proportional. Why do you think there is that under-representation? I mean, you gave a few reasons, you spoke about how some males may not be willing to wait at least 8 years to become an APN. But apart from that, do you think there is any other reasons? So, another thing is, I feel the role of APN in Singapore is still not very well-broadcasted to the general public. So, in general, first, the impact of nursing has always been portrayed as a caring profession, it's a compassionate profession. And then, these attributes of compassion and caring has always been linked to females, per se. So, yes, no doubt males are compassionate and caring too, they can be too. But then, generally, I don't think these two attributes are what draw males into the profession. So, I feel that one of the ways that the role of APN should be advertised in Singapore is about the knowledge and skill that APNs have beyond making people feel better. Like, they do have the clinical expertise, that it is a knowledge-intensive occupation. I think if we actually highlight that this part, we can actually attract more males into the profession. It's not just about us being caring, it is the knowledge-intensive occupation. We do it while it takes to make people, beyond making them feel better, beyond the caring attributes. Yeah, that's so true. But then, okay, that being said, do you think it's important and necessary to have more men in the APN workforce? Or is it just fine as it is? I feel, regardless of profession, it's always good to have a gender balance. Because different gender bring different characteristics. So, it's always good to have a gender balance. However, I don't see it as a necessity, per se, to increase the number of males. I feel that nursing has always been a predominantly female environment. So, males shouldn't be seen as shining knights in armour to save the profession, just because they are so scared. I mean, there are males with potential attributes that I'm sure we can tap on. But then, these are just those with good attributes. That doesn't mean you should attract just because you are male. We need you in the profession. I don't think it actually matters that much. You spoke about gender balance that would benefit professions across professions, right? So, specifically to APN practice, how do you think gender balance will benefit APN practice? So, generally, I think for the public, at least the older generation, they still think that nurses are female, doctors are male. So, to them, I've actually seen how the public can respond differently when a female and a male professional communicate with them. I'm not too sure whether it's due to some entrenched cultural belief or what. So, having a louder male voice in the profession can help, I feel, in a way to raise the image by saying that it's not just something that females can do. Another thing would be to let the doctors' counterpart know that they do have... Because now, the majority of the APNs I work with are generally female. So, having a male inside and in terms of masculine characteristics, sometimes they are less emotional-driven. They can actually be more objective in certain things. Doesn't mean patient care, be it in terms of clinical leadership. So, I feel that that's where they can actually bring their attributes in. I want to go back to talking about the public perception. You spoke about how you've observed the patients treating a male and a female healthcare professional quite differently. Does it apply to nursing? I think it depends. Not every patient, per se. For some patients, there are definitely patients who feel more comfortable with female nurses. But there are also some patients who can tell that when it's being handled by a male nurse, they tend to be... Not saying more respectful, I don't think that's a good word. But in a way, they will feel that he's not the usual missy taking care of me. They may not know who he is because he's someone that's not the usual female nurse taking care of them. Their attitude is just slightly varied. Some of the more demanding patients can be a bit less hostile. Honestly, I don't know what's the reason, but some of them display different attitudes. How does that make you feel? Generally, I'm okay with it. But just certain parts, for example, to me I'm more affected when I tell them I'm actually studying to be an APN. They say, is it your route to become a doctor? I say, no, I just want to become an APN. So they keep thinking that this is actually the stepping stone to become a doctor. So to me, that part affects me more, but not so much. Because to me, you can't really change, I feel, among the older generation. I'm not inclined to change their perception towards men and females. Do you think riding on this stereotype and public perception, do you then think that having more men in the APN workforce will have an influence on the acceptance of APN in healthcare? I think having more male representation in the APN workforce will help to attract more male nurses into the profession. So to me, that's the main advantage of having more males. It helps to change the public perception that now that males are doing good in nursing, they can also be clinical specialists in nursing. That's one thing. It's no longer a predominantly female-dominated profession. And then it can also help to increase the acceptance of nursing among the younger population, and increase the male intake in the nursing workforce. How about healthcare consumers? The acceptance of patients. Towards APN in general? Yeah, because now, what we've discovered is that acceptance towards APN is not optimal yet, but it's growing. So I'm just wondering, if having more men in the APN workforce, would that accelerate that acceptance? Would patients be more accepting of seeing an APN because he's male? Actually, no. I don't really see why, or just because there's quite a few male APNs. I don't think it's the perception that because there are fewer male APNs, this profession is not being recognised by the public. But rather how this role is being portrayed to the public, which could actually let down the people who have less male entering the profession. Because like I said, it's always depending on compassion or care, but it's not compassion and care that saves the patient physically per se. So it is a knowledge-intensive occupation. So if you went on this, it can actually help to attract more male into the profession. But let's not so much to, because there are less male in the profession, the public will think, Oh, APNs, I understand, APNs maybe, because there's no male or female, it's not good. I don't think, at least in current modern society, I don't think the general bias is that strong. I prefer to do so. I love it. I love how you describe APN practice as a knowledge-intensive occupation. That's very good. It's a very accurate definition of what an APN does. Generally, I know you don't really think that having more men would change the public impression or public acceptance. But then do you think that having more men in the APN workforce will have an influence on the professional image of nursing in general? Image, yes. Because I think that, like I said earlier, sometimes nursing has handmaidens because in historical, we are all females generally. And then, be it whatsoever, comic or, sorry, like you see last time, it's always the female nurse and the male doctor. So, as a professional image, yes, if we do have more male APNs stepping up, it will change the perception that Singapore Nursing has evolved to the stage that even male wanted to join this female predominant industry and can do as well as a female as well. So, it's definitely good for the professional image because now that you know that it's good enough to attract both genders. Then wouldn't that, I mean I'm just thinking, wouldn't that translate into public acceptance? Having a good professional image, does it translate into public acceptance? That's my question. Okay, I think, probably because I work in the tribute ward and then my target patient population, generally whatever perception they have are quite deeply entrenched. So, you know, they are not exposed to social media, so I'm not too sure whether all this, I mean I've never asked them, they have never said that, oh how come there's no male APNs attending to me. So, I don't think I can comment much about that. So, to me, it definitely raises the public perception but at least from my personal encounter and among my friends, I don't see any of them experiencing people asking them, hey how come there's no male APN attending to me. Okay, so that aside, how do you think we can improve the recruitment of men into the APN profession? I mean you did say that there's a value of having more men in APN practice so that we can recruit more males into our RM workforce in the first place. So, how do you think we can improve the recruitment of men? So, first, the one I mentioned is the rebranding of the APN role in Singapore. I feel when I see nurse practitioners overseas, they actually have a much greater autonomy in whatever they do. I feel the APN Singapore and the branding of it is still very much, it's not very, it's not adequate for the public to know what they're doing per se. So, again, they always brand nurses as just a caring professional profession, which is no doubt true. However, if they don't highlight the technical expertise behind it, it's quite hard to attract males into the profession because generally caring, compassionate, generally they're attributed to females. So, I don't think just branding it as caring and compassionate is sufficient to draw males into the profession. I mean generally males, not all, but generally they can be a bit more curious and ambitious. So, they will want their role to be able to move to the public as something that's with a professional image, clinical competency, what they can do, etc. So, you spoke about rebranding. How can we rebrand? What kind of modes of delivery? So, for example, during Nurses' Day, usually we have those campaigns and all. I think it's improving. I think we are seeing more APNs being featured. So, probably just a deeper account of what the APN can do into the public perception, like what they are doing. And focusing more on the clinical expertise part. So, that part can let them know that because we know that some of them are actually seeing APNs in the primary healthcare setting now. So, if you let them know that these people are actually trained with at least a Master's qualification, they have some clinical experience, they are actually in safe hands, I think it will be good. Instead of letting them feel that, how come I'm actually a nurse and not a doctor? Because they may not know how exactly is the APN trained. So, apart from rebranding the APN profession, how else can we improve the recruitment of men? I think also, in general, APNs per se, it should be an independent entity. Instead of just one that is being totally subsumed by the nursing model per se. Like now, it's just from a clinical track, it's just one part of it. So, I feel because it's one that's very specialised per se, it should have their own, how should I put it? At least for mine now, in my hospital, we do have a department of our own. Last time, and I think for some other organisation, it used to be under the department per se. So, maybe I'm under the ward, there will be an APN counselling. Instead of having a department of their own, they can help to promote greater autonomy per se, compared to just one that's just another route in a clinical track. So, are you suggesting that the APNs should be on a separate career track? So, their own career development, professional development track? Yes. Then, apart from that, which will make it clearer for professional development, how else do you think we can recruit more men? Should it be top-down? Should it be bottom-up? How do we make sure that we get good male applicants? If it's top-down, then it should be done by a male senior executive. It's a bit hard to go top-down and done by a female executive. They should be able to see their own gender rising so high up in the profession. They know, there's a chance that they'll get there someday. A lot of senior positions are female-predominated. If it's top-down, if someone is giving a talk, the target audience is male nurses per se, it would be good to have a male representation from senior management. We do have male chief nurses, male directors of nursing in Singapore. So, that's a huge step forward. We don't have that many male leaders. In the first place, the existing female positions are really female-predominated. That's something that can't change because these are people who have worked for the past 30-40 years. Do you think that is a barrier for deterring men from pursuing the career track? Because for more female bosses, is it? I think so, probably. Generally, I feel like if you ask someone to come to a place where all your bosses are female, and you're the only male there, there will be a little bit of apprehension. Because obviously, you're in a place that's probably more well-mixed with gender, gender-balanced kind of thing. So, that could be the reason when they say, majority of nurses are already female, all the big bosses are female, would I fit in this industry if I want to rise out there? That's interesting. Do you really think they think that way? I'm also wondering. Not too sure exactly actually. So, like I said, I've seen female nurses doing very well in the industry. And also, male nurses who left after a while. So, I'm not too sure whether those cases could be isolated cases where they just couldn't click so well with their female bosses. That could be a reason, if there's no mutual understanding. But that could be isolated cases. So, to me, I've not encountered that many male nurses to make this comment. You spoke about how males are more career-driven, they are also very impatient, they can't wait for the 8 years. Some males may be very apprehensive about having to work closely with female bosses. Apart from all these things and all these reasons, do you think there are other existing barriers that deter men from pursuing the APN track? So, to me, the question has always been deterring male from entering the nursing profession rather than deterring male from being an AP. I feel it's always the people in the frank. But do you think that men are less academically inclined? No. I've seen men who are very academically driven. But then these people left us to do research and policy. I've seen these people who are very academically driven, very ambitious in their career. These are people who are top-rated, they didn't want to wait for the 8 years. They could have gone on to take their masters after 2 or 3 years. Then do you think we should shorten the years of experience for eligibility? I think for now, 5 years is actually okay. But I feel that we are moving a big step forward because last time, they only sought out one nursing officer to be part of the program. So, I think now, 5 years, but they allowed us to take on the program. I think it's actually quite good enough because you don't need a certain number of experience to know whether you are really cut out for this. You spoke about some advantages of having more males in the APN practice. One is about professional image. Can you think of any other advantages? I think for APNs, beyond the first few years, there are very clinically intensive hours. After that, they are actually looking into more clinical leadership. Clinical leads for workgroups, quality etc. In that case, I think that sometimes having a male in that position or within that will help because you can actually... I feel that we have different characteristics. Having that will help because especially in the clinical leadership part, we are actually supposed to hit our clinical workgroups etc. after that first few years. Because I feel that APN is not just about the clinical part. Beyond that, you are expected to take on clinical leadership roles. You spoke about how male and female bring in different characteristics. Can you share a bit more about it? Not all the time, but sometimes, for example, females that have female bosses, they tend to be very detail-oriented. But sometimes, they may not take a step back to see the whole picture. Whereas males tend to be a bit more level-headed. They probably may not be as detail-oriented, but then they can see the entire big picture. When these two work together, I feel it's better. Because if you just focus on the big picture without going into the details, it's not right. But if you just focus on the micromanaging without looking at the big details, it's also not right. Apart from that, needing to have a better balance in clinical leadership, is there any other advantages that you can see having more men in the APN plus workgroup? Hmm... So besides the public perception, besides bringing in different attributes, I feel that's worth it. Because I don't see that I'm male and male in fashion per se. Now let's talk about the disadvantages. What are the disadvantages of having men in the APN practice? Are there things that they can't do because they're men? Honestly, I'm not too sure. Because I know at least for male nurses, generally we won't put them in charge of taking care of senior patients. Okay. So I'm not too sure for the male APN side, will they be able to do it? If they're like doctors, they just need a female chaperone, that will be okay. But I'm not too sure whether, will they not be allowed to do certain things just because they're male. Because in nursing for example, we don't ask a male nurse as much as possible to insert a female catheter. True. So I'm not too sure whether we'll just actually bring in male APNs because I'm not accounted enough to see for myself whether that part affects them. Certain more invasive procedures for females, they will not be able to participate. Or they will always need a female chaperone, which compared to females, we can just do it ourselves. But they will just need a female chaperone because they need to do physical examination. Because for APNs, it's not a physical examination. So when they do it, they will need a chaperone, which I think they will need. But then compared to, it will be a bit more hassle. Means they need an additional manpower to go with them to do it. If they were even allowed to do it. Because for certain procedures, I'm not too sure whether they'll be allowed to do it. Then that sounds very, that sounds quite bad, right? Because then you spend so much time to train a male APN, and then end up this male APN, his practice is limited. His scope of practice becomes limited. When we're trying to widen the scope of APN practice. So I'm not too sure whether, will they be limited or will they just need a chaperone. Even needing a chaperone also requires manpower. But then that being said, male doctors also need chaperone. So there's this give and take, right? Correct. Okay, then, what areas, considering the limitations that you know of, that you know men can't do certain things and certain skills, what areas and what specialty do you think male APNs can play a significant role in healthcare? ED. Oh, you mean besides APN, right? No, okay, so let me repeat. What areas or specialty male APNs can play a significant role in healthcare? So you're talking about ED, is it? Yeah, ED. Actually besides ED, probably because the one that I heard who's doing very well is the ED APN. But actually, I feel perhaps community nursing may be a bit tough. Perhaps because if you have to go to a patient's house below, there's always this consideration there. But besides community APN, if you have to make house visits, I think the rest are actually okay. You spoke about ED, it was a very fast response. So what is it about ED that makes a male APN be able to flourish there and perform well there? I'm speaking from someone that I heard from a friend who actually knows a male ED APN. So I think when they are excited and driven, they are always on the ball. ED was always seen in many patients. Sometimes when people are stressed in a situation, some of the doctors may not be as good. So having a male APN there to ensure that, you don't mess with my nurses. I feel sometimes towards male and female nurses, some doctors also unknowingly behave a bit differently. If it's a male nurse, sometimes they will be a bit more okay. Less hostile? Yeah, less hostile per se. So having one in a fast-paced environment, in a very dynamic environment in school, to have a male APN to hold the fort in that sense, I think that's where they can actually flourish. Anywhere else? So we know that the community is out because there's just too much hassle. They have to bring a chaperone along, and they probably will face a lot of sensitive issues if they are alone with a female at home. Anywhere else you think they would flourish in? Actually, I feel after that first few years of clinical experience, they will flourish in the clinical lead position. That means in the clinical leadership part, where they are handling the quality, the workgroup, the evidence-based workgroup for example, to have a male predominant figure. But then anywhere else, I think it's actually pretty similar. So you think that they will do well in leadership? Yeah, leadership and administration. Is it? Correct. Okay, that's good. Apart from community, is there any other areas that you think that they will face problems in? Besides community, no, actually I think it's okay. It will still be quite versatile like a female, right? Not much difference. Okay, before we end, I have just one other thought that I would like to discuss. So when we look at gender in other professions, maybe in the corporate world, there is always a lot more men, right? And it puts females at a disadvantage inevitably, right? I mean, they are trying to level that out, but there is still that disadvantage towards females because it's a male-dominated community. But in nursing, right, where we have a female-dominated community, why is it that the males are not getting that negative stigma or not getting that negative... Yeah, not getting that negative feeling that females get in a male-dominated corporate world. Instead, we celebrate when we have more men in our industry. We think that it's easier to identify an outstanding male nurse even though he can do the same thing as a female nurse. Why do you think that there is this phenomenon in our female-dominated workforce? So first things first, I feel that... Okay, maybe before you share what you feel, do you agree with my observation? Not entirely. I mean, part of it, but not entirely. Okay. So the part that you said that, you know, probably in the corporate world, sometimes women feel a bit at a certain disadvantage because it's predominantly male. Yeah. I feel there's this part to men as well. Obviously, we are talking about male nurses who are... Male nurses, those who are maybe not the queen of the crop, you know, they are just like... Yeah, right. So I feel among them, having a predominant female senior organisation, there are times that, like I said before, probably because they can identify more with their female subordinates, you know, what are the senior characteristics. So some male nurses who are a bit more vocal, I don't know whether they will be seen as, you know, a bit more threatening to the female supervisor or they just don't really like, you know, how some male nurses carry themselves because it's very domineering, you know, very vocal. So they are not very comfortable because nurses in general is still a very... a profession that doesn't really speak up that much, let's say. Wouldn't it then be better if we have more people, more nurses that are... We change the culture where we have more vocal nurses. Yes, that's provided the senior management are receptive to it. Okay, yeah. Yeah, correct. You're good at saying something, yeah. So this is the part that I feel that could put them at a disadvantage because, you know, because their core attributes is a bit different from the female supervisor. Yeah, that actually causes a certain level of... So in a way, you know, they won't be stopped highly upon because they feel that, hey, this one is different from the norm, let's say. So to me, that's the main part. And then the part that they are celebrated, they are the part I agree. I think the part that they are celebrated is because it's just a movement that they wanted to raise the profession of nursing, right? Getting more mail, spend less in pastries, half-day, yeah. So, yeah, it's just to raise a public perception of nursing. I'm not too sure whether... It's like when someone that is not the norm gets something good, usually people will just celebrate it, and let them know, okay. But to me, I... Yeah, so it's just to raise a public perception, I guess. Yeah, I agree with you. This is something that really... Yeah, something I think a lot about as well. Okay, before I end this interview, do you have any other comments that you want to speak about regarding men in APN practice or recruitment of men? So, I think that mainly if you want to attract more men into the industry, and making these people eventually want to become APN, is we have to highlight the... How... What the value of this role. I think it's still not very well-treated to the public. So, to me, that's the main thing if you want to attract more men into the industry. Okay. That's all? Yeah. Okay, thank you. I will end the recording now. Thank you. Thank you.

segments.text: Okay, let's start by sharing your experience of being recruited into the MN program about
two or three years back.
So, for me, I think probably first I made myself, I made it quite clear to my bosses
that I'm interested in clinical, so I was in the clinical interest.
So, usually during our appraisal, there's always the three years and five years plan.
So, mine was always three years to take the MN course and five years to become an APN.
So, it was known right from the start.
Okay, so, but specifically, I mean you spoke about clinical track, but did you know that
you want to be a nurse clinician or an advanced practice nurse?
Oh, I knew I want to be an advanced practice nurse.
So, actually back in undergraduate days, we had a lecture by an APN then.
Yeah, I think she was a Cardio APN and I was quite inspired by her then.
So, I knew this was the track I wanted to take.
So, you only expressed your interest through your appraisal?
Actually, usually for us, they will speak to us, they will on and off be informal or formal.
So, every time they come and talk to me, my answer will be the same.
I want to go down the APN track.
When you talk about they, who do you refer to?
So far, in nursing, there will be your direct court supervisor, usually the court assistant,
and we have the assistant director of nursing who actually oversee a few wards.
So, I actually made myself quite clear to both the direct supervisor and also assistant director of nursing.
When they make their rounds.
At that point, how many years are you into your RN role?
I think I was probably the first year, I was actually known that I wanted to go down this route.
But I mean, because of the SMB requirements as a first year RN, you wouldn't qualify for the MN program.
Did your organization sort of prepare you for it?
So, they actually sent me for the advanced diploma program, specialization that I was interested in.
So, I actually went for advanced diploma one year plus after I started working.
And then when I came back, they actually, I continued what I was doing before that.
But then just around a few months to a year before I started my program,
they sent me out for rotation to different clinical wards with different specialists.
Do you happen to know if there were certain things that your superiors were looking out for when recruiting you into this track?
Certain things, so what I heard is they would want a person with good academic results.
At least because I heard there is a 3-year program.
So, another one would be one who demonstrated clinical interest during day-to-day ward rounds.
Because someone that is somewhat recognized by the medical counterparts, because you will be working very closely with them.
So, I guess they also seek opinion from the doctors in the ward, maybe who they work with on the ground and all.
Okay, maybe you can share a bit more also about your current APN career track, right?
Which phase are you in?
Okay, I'm currently doing my internship.
So, I'm reaching the midpoint.
So, following that, I'll be taking my national exam at the end of this year.
And then if I successfully pass, I'll pass out next year.
Okay, so now I'm going to touch a bit about gender.
So, when your superior was selecting potential APNs, do you think that they considered the gender of the nurse?
I don't think gender actually is a deal-breaker in that sense.
Or you must be a female or you cannot be.
I don't think so, but it just so happened that in my ward, there are just very few male nurses.
And those who were present in my ward, they just didn't express interest in this route.
So, I won't say it's because of any gender bias, but they selected me.
So, if I would phrase it a bit differently, do you think that it was easier or more difficult for you to be selected into the MN program previously because you were female?
I don't think there's a difference actually.
So, it's neither more difficult nor easier actually.
Why do you say that though?
Because I feel what they had in mind then was they had certain attributes that they are looking for in an APN.
And gender is definitely not one of them.
So, they have things like, okay, next time we want the APN to be a jack-of-all-trades.
So, you have to be doing a little bit of research, a little bit of clinicals.
They wanted the APN to be someone who is able to at least communicate decently.
So, there's certain criteria that they were looking out for and gender is not one of them.
Okay. I suppose there's an interview process to being selected. Maybe you can tell me a bit about that.
So, the interview process mainly was to reinforce.
So, they can just ask us, why do you want to take on this job?
Because it's going to be a two-year rigorous program.
It's going to be a one-year internship.
It's not like a short duration. You have to actually commit to it.
So, they wanted to ensure that we are up for this, we are ready for this.
And then, they actually asked us what we intend to do next time when you pass out.
And of course, what do you think your strengths, your weakness and how to work on that.
After being selected, did your superiors speak about things like your life stage, like your personal life stage?
Do you have plans of settling down and all that?
Yeah. So, they talked about it's advisable not to have a baby in this period of time
because it's going to be hard to cope with your studies and internship.
Even though it's not like they do not allow you to, but you can tell that it's generally discouraged
because of the intensity of the course.
They did ask what's your plan in terms of personal life in the next few years.
And then, what did you say to your interviewer?
I think because I was still young then, so to me that wasn't an issue.
But this has been an issue I saw amongst some of my other colleagues that had plans initially.
And because they are in different stage of life, it actually is a deterrence for them to go on this program.
So, you are speaking about your female colleagues or your male colleagues?
Female colleagues actually.
Okay. So, now considering this about life stages, childbearing,
do you then now think that it will be more difficult for a female to get selected into the program?
I don't think it's more difficult for a female to get selected,
but rather there will be more consideration for a female to see whether she wants to get on this program or not.
Because some common things I heard will be like,
if I go on this program, does it mean that I can't give birth in the next three years?
Does it mean that you have to take a step back from your family life for the next three years?
So, I realized that friends with very young, just given birth with very young kids,
they are the ones that struggle the most.
Compared to people whose kids are pretty old already,
they can actually spend more time on their studies instead of taking care of their child.
So, there is a difference, but it's not so much the criteria to be selected,
but rather whether one wants to take on that role to go on this study or not.
Do you then think that there are gender biases present in the professional development of RNs in the workforce?
Not just pertaining to development into an APN track, but across all tracks.
Do you think that there is a gender bias?
I don't think there is a gender bias,
but because even though the percentage of male nurses have increased over the year,
it's actually in a slow, gradual increase.
So, people who are already in a senior position,
the majority are actually female nurses already.
Sometimes, what you are looking out for,
sometimes when people look out for the next generation of leaders,
they will look out for people with similar characteristics.
Therefore, I feel that probably, unknowingly sometimes,
they may actually feel that females generally possess the same characteristics,
knowing the same thing as what they can bring to the workforce.
So, probably certain supervisors will be a bit more geared towards that, unknowingly.
Are you implying that female leaders tend to look for someone that is similar to them,
and it happens to be a female nurse that would exhibit similar traits?
Sometimes. But that being said, I feel that even though male nurses are under minority,
there is a certain advantage to it.
I have seen male nurses, if you are good,
you are actually much more easily recognised than your female counterparts,
because they are so scarce.
If one stood out, that person can be given a lot more opportunities
compared to his peers who are females.
Because he just stands out more easily, because he is a male,
and he can just outshine, because he is a male and he can do his good,
compared to his female counterparts, he just managed to get some upper hand.
So, are you just to clarify, are you implying that if a male and a female nurse
does the same quality of work, same competency, but the male will seem more outstanding?
Probably because of certain, sometimes when,
be it, I don't know whether there is some masculine characteristics,
compared to a male and a female, if they are of equal level of competence, of knowledge,
and because of how rare it is to get a male who is very good,
because there are so few males around,
sometimes that person may be getting a bit more opportunities,
at least shine out a bit more.
Just because he is so different, right?
Correct.
Then do you think that nursing leaders take into consideration the gender of the RN
when nominating him or her for the MM programme?
I don't think so. I don't think that matters at all.
I don't think that is part of the consideration.
But probably it just so happens because there are more,
there are certain criteria for you to get enrolled into the MM programme,
one of which is experience.
Previously, the majority of the candidates are actually in the nurse clinician stage.
So, in the first place, among the nurse clinicians,
it is really female-predominated because of previous enrollment characteristics.
So, that is the reason why there are more female APNs compared to male.
I understand.
In your organisation, do you have any male colleagues that are APNs?
We used to have one, but he left us.
Do you know why he left?
I think he was just, he actually, he was quite, he has been an APN for quite some time.
And then, he feels that he wasn't, I think at that point in time, there was some ambiguity.
So, he feels that he was not practising at all his life.
And due to personal reasons, he chose to leave us.
So, that was quite in the early stages.
Yes.
Okay.
Just now, so, okay.
So, apart from this one other APN, do you know of any other male APN in the APN workforce?
Yes.
Not in this hospital, but in other hospitals, yes.
And would you agree with me that there's very few of them?
Definitely.
There are much fewer than female.
So, you mentioned in your ward that there are also very few males.
But these few male nurses, they don't exhibit interest in the APN track.
Do you happen to know why?
I feel it.
I don't think it's due to, okay, I've honestly, I've never wondered why they have no interest in being an APN.
Because to me, it's not about, or because you're male or you're female.
Yeah.
Because whether you have a clinical interest or not.
And then, quite a few of my male friends back in undergrad, they actually chose to take on administrative lead research.
So, they chose to further their study shortly after entering the profession.
So, maybe two or three years into the profession.
I'm not too sure, because one of it is, for APN, you need five years to go on this course.
I don't know if some males will have the, to them, it's still quite, you know, five years to go on this course,
another two years of study, another one year of intern, eight years to become an APN.
Probably, to them, they will have gone on to, they have a need to organize, they have a goal to do other things.
Be it research, be it policy, et cetera.
But why do you think that males have a greater tendency to not want to wait it out?
I think it's always the societal pressure for a male having to be the main breadwinner, even though times are changing.
But to them, there's, I think in general, there's still this mentality that,
okay, if I'm going to get married and support my family, I need to be, I need to earn as much as I can, per se.
So, do I, should I wait, like, and even for five years as a minimum, it doesn't mean five years you will definitely go for the course, right?
So I may need a minimum of eight years to go it, you know.
So sometimes, probably if I go on to take another higher education, I could actually do it much earlier.
Based on your experience and observation, male RNs tend to go into research?
No, actually, the undergrads are at risk.
Those who actually have a degree, they tend to gravitate more towards policy, towards research.
Okay, so that's where we are losing our male graduates to.
For clinicals.
That's interesting, because I would think that there is this stereotype amongst men that they are more clinical.
Do you think my stereotype is wrong?
I think, I don't think they feel that, okay, at least what I've seen is they feel they are,
so if you look, I think if you look across the different specialty, there will always be a few specialty that are more male than other specialty.
For example, in the emergency department, in the ICU, in the OTE.
So I guess that to them, probably, they will feel that, okay, they can, they will have advantage in this, in such things,
be it in terms of physical strength or whatsoever.
But not so much because I think they are better in clinical, per se.
So you would think, okay, so maybe let's explore a bit deeper.
Why would you think that, why do you think that there are more male prominent in the ED and ICU and OT?
I feel, okay, I can't speak too much about OT, but at least for ED and ICU,
one thing is it's a faster pace and then it's more action-packed.
In terms of, as I said, ED, in terms of physical strength, in terms of violent patient and all,
and this could be the attribute that actually draw male nurses into that specialty.
So compared to general ward, per se, when one has to take on many patients,
you have to attend to the basic care,
I don't think, probably this part will not seem as attractive to them,
compared to the fast-paced, faster-paced ED and ICU environment.
That's a very interesting observation.
Then do you think, because now, I mean, we both agree that there are so few men in the APM practice,
do you think that there is, because, maybe let me share some statistics with you.
So currently we have 11% of males in the RN workforce, which is already a great improvement from the past.
But now, currently in our APM workforce, we only have about 5%.
So there's a, it's not proportional.
Why do you think there is that under-representation?
I mean, you gave a few reasons, you spoke about how some males may not be willing to wait at least 8 years to become an APN.
But apart from that, do you think there is any other reasons?
So, another thing is, I feel the role of APN in Singapore is still not very well-broadcasted to the general public.
So, in general, first, the impact of nursing has always been portrayed as a caring profession,
it's a compassionate profession.
And then, these attributes of compassion and caring has always been linked to females, per se.
So, yes, no doubt males are compassionate and caring too, they can be too.
But then, generally, I don't think these two attributes are what draw males into the profession.
So, I feel that one of the ways that the role of APN should be advertised in Singapore
is about the knowledge and skill that APNs have beyond making people feel better.
Like, they do have the clinical expertise, that it is a knowledge-intensive occupation.
I think if we actually highlight that this part, we can actually attract more males into the profession.
It's not just about us being caring, it is the knowledge-intensive occupation.
We do it while it takes to make people, beyond making them feel better, beyond the caring attributes.
Yeah, that's so true.
But then, okay, that being said, do you think it's important and necessary to have more men in the APN workforce?
Or is it just fine as it is?
I feel, regardless of profession, it's always good to have a gender balance.
Because different gender bring different characteristics.
So, it's always good to have a gender balance.
However, I don't see it as a necessity, per se, to increase the number of males.
I feel that nursing has always been a predominantly female environment.
So, males shouldn't be seen as shining knights in armour to save the profession, just because they are so scared.
I mean, there are males with potential attributes that I'm sure we can tap on.
But then, these are just those with good attributes.
That doesn't mean you should attract just because you are male.
We need you in the profession.
I don't think it actually matters that much.
You spoke about gender balance that would benefit professions across professions, right?
So, specifically to APN practice, how do you think gender balance will benefit APN practice?
So, generally, I think for the public, at least the older generation, they still think that nurses are female, doctors are male.
So, to them, I've actually seen how the public can respond differently when a female and a male professional communicate with them.
I'm not too sure whether it's due to some entrenched cultural belief or what.
So, having a louder male voice in the profession can help, I feel, in a way to raise the image by saying that it's not just something that females can do.
Another thing would be to let the doctors' counterpart know that they do have...
Because now, the majority of the APNs I work with are generally female.
So, having a male inside and in terms of masculine characteristics, sometimes they are less emotional-driven.
They can actually be more objective in certain things.
Doesn't mean patient care, be it in terms of clinical leadership.
So, I feel that that's where they can actually bring their attributes in.
I want to go back to talking about the public perception.
You spoke about how you've observed the patients treating a male and a female healthcare professional quite differently.
Does it apply to nursing?
I think it depends. Not every patient, per se.
For some patients, there are definitely patients who feel more comfortable with female nurses.
But there are also some patients who can tell that when it's being handled by a male nurse, they tend to be...
Not saying more respectful, I don't think that's a good word.
But in a way, they will feel that he's not the usual missy taking care of me.
They may not know who he is because he's someone that's not the usual female nurse taking care of them.
Their attitude is just slightly varied.
Some of the more demanding patients can be a bit less hostile.
Honestly, I don't know what's the reason, but some of them display different attitudes.
How does that make you feel?
Generally, I'm okay with it.
But just certain parts, for example, to me I'm more affected when I tell them I'm actually studying to be an APN.
They say, is it your route to become a doctor? I say, no, I just want to become an APN.
So they keep thinking that this is actually the stepping stone to become a doctor.
So to me, that part affects me more, but not so much.
Because to me, you can't really change, I feel, among the older generation.
I'm not inclined to change their perception towards men and females.
Do you think riding on this stereotype and public perception,
do you then think that having more men in the APN workforce will have an influence on the acceptance of APN in healthcare?
I think having more male representation in the APN workforce will help to attract more male nurses into the profession.
So to me, that's the main advantage of having more males.
It helps to change the public perception that now that males are doing good in nursing,
they can also be clinical specialists in nursing. That's one thing.
It's no longer a predominantly female-dominated profession.
And then it can also help to increase the acceptance of nursing among the younger population,
and increase the male intake in the nursing workforce.
How about healthcare consumers?
The acceptance of patients.
Towards APN in general?
Yeah, because now, what we've discovered is that acceptance towards APN is not optimal yet, but it's growing.
So I'm just wondering, if having more men in the APN workforce, would that accelerate that acceptance?
Would patients be more accepting of seeing an APN because he's male?
Actually, no.
I don't really see why, or just because there's quite a few male APNs.
I don't think it's the perception that because there are fewer male APNs, this profession is not being recognised by the public.
But rather how this role is being portrayed to the public, which could actually let down the people who have less male entering the profession.
Because like I said, it's always depending on compassion or care, but it's not compassion and care that saves the patient physically per se.
So it is a knowledge-intensive occupation.
So if you went on this, it can actually help to attract more male into the profession.
But let's not so much to, because there are less male in the profession, the public will think,
Oh, APNs, I understand, APNs maybe, because there's no male or female, it's not good.
I don't think, at least in current modern society, I don't think the general bias is that strong.
I prefer to do so.
I love it. I love how you describe APN practice as a knowledge-intensive occupation.
That's very good. It's a very accurate definition of what an APN does.
Generally, I know you don't really think that having more men would change the public impression or public acceptance.
But then do you think that having more men in the APN workforce will have an influence on the professional image of nursing in general?
Image, yes.
Because I think that, like I said earlier, sometimes nursing has handmaidens because in historical, we are all females generally.
And then, be it whatsoever, comic or, sorry, like you see last time, it's always the female nurse and the male doctor.
So, as a professional image, yes, if we do have more male APNs stepping up, it will change the perception that Singapore Nursing has evolved to the stage that
even male wanted to join this female predominant industry and can do as well as a female as well.
So, it's definitely good for the professional image because now that you know that it's good enough to attract both genders.
Then wouldn't that, I mean I'm just thinking, wouldn't that translate into public acceptance?
Having a good professional image, does it translate into public acceptance? That's my question.
Okay, I think, probably because I work in the tribute ward and then my target patient population,
generally whatever perception they have are quite deeply entrenched.
So, you know, they are not exposed to social media, so I'm not too sure whether all this, I mean I've never asked them,
they have never said that, oh how come there's no male APNs attending to me.
So, I don't think I can comment much about that.
So, to me, it definitely raises the public perception but at least from my personal encounter and among my friends,
I don't see any of them experiencing people asking them, hey how come there's no male APN attending to me.
Okay, so that aside, how do you think we can improve the recruitment of men into the APN profession?
I mean you did say that there's a value of having more men in APN practice so that we can recruit more males into our RM workforce in the first place.
So, how do you think we can improve the recruitment of men?
So, first, the one I mentioned is the rebranding of the APN role in Singapore.
I feel when I see nurse practitioners overseas, they actually have a much greater autonomy in whatever they do.
I feel the APN Singapore and the branding of it is still very much, it's not very, it's not adequate for the public to know what they're doing per se.
So, again, they always brand nurses as just a caring professional profession, which is no doubt true.
However, if they don't highlight the technical expertise behind it, it's quite hard to attract males into the profession
because generally caring, compassionate, generally they're attributed to females.
So, I don't think just branding it as caring and compassionate is sufficient to draw males into the profession.
I mean generally males, not all, but generally they can be a bit more curious and ambitious.
So, they will want their role to be able to move to the public as something that's with a professional image, clinical competency, what they can do, etc.
So, you spoke about rebranding. How can we rebrand? What kind of modes of delivery?
So, for example, during Nurses' Day, usually we have those campaigns and all.
I think it's improving. I think we are seeing more APNs being featured.
So, probably just a deeper account of what the APN can do into the public perception, like what they are doing.
And focusing more on the clinical expertise part.
So, that part can let them know that because we know that some of them are actually seeing APNs in the primary healthcare setting now.
So, if you let them know that these people are actually trained with at least a Master's qualification,
they have some clinical experience, they are actually in safe hands, I think it will be good.
Instead of letting them feel that, how come I'm actually a nurse and not a doctor?
Because they may not know how exactly is the APN trained.
So, apart from rebranding the APN profession, how else can we improve the recruitment of men?
I think also, in general, APNs per se, it should be an independent entity.
Instead of just one that is being totally subsumed by the nursing model per se.
Like now, it's just from a clinical track, it's just one part of it.
So, I feel because it's one that's very specialised per se, it should have their own, how should I put it?
At least for mine now, in my hospital, we do have a department of our own.
Last time, and I think for some other organisation, it used to be under the department per se.
So, maybe I'm under the ward, there will be an APN counselling.
Instead of having a department of their own, they can help to promote greater autonomy per se,
compared to just one that's just another route in a clinical track.
So, are you suggesting that the APNs should be on a separate career track?
So, their own career development, professional development track?
Yes.
Then, apart from that, which will make it clearer for professional development,
how else do you think we can recruit more men?
Should it be top-down? Should it be bottom-up?
How do we make sure that we get good male applicants?
If it's top-down, then it should be done by a male senior executive.
It's a bit hard to go top-down and done by a female executive.
